Nominativo.

I/YOU/HE/SHE/IT/WE/YOU/THEY : yo, tu , el ella, nosotros, ...

Posesivo: se usan como adjetivos .
MY/YOUR/HIS/HER/ITS/OUR/YOUR/THEIR : mío,tuyo,suyo,nuestro, vuestro...


I-my
you-your (iur)
he-his
she-her
it-its
we-our
they-their (deir)

She is MY sister.
He likes HIS English class.


Pronombres Objeto


ME/YOU/HIM/HER/IT/US/YOU/THEM 

I-me
you-you
he-him
she-her
it-it
we-us
they-them ( dem )

This class is for me.
This class is for you
This class is for them
John plays with us
My brother told me ( me dijo ) that....
They saw him in the park



We saw her at the theatre . // La vimos en el teatro
Helen studies english with us. // Estudia inglés con nosotros.

PRONOMBRES POSESIVOS:

MINE/YOURS/HIS/HERS/OURS/YOURS/THEIRS : mio, tuyo, suyo,nuestro, vuestro, suyo.

this book is mine



PRONOMBRES REFLEXIVOS

MYSELF/YOURSELF/HIMSELF/HERSELF/ITSELF/OURSELVES/YOURSELVES/THEMSELVES

He hurts himself       //  El se lastimó-
She burned herself    //   Ella se quemó
He himself will come //    el mismo vendrá

He went to NY by himself // Fue a NY solo.
I don't like to go to the theatre by myself // No me gusta ir solo al   teatro.




THIS : cuando un objeto está cerca - singular.
THAT: objetos distantes  - singular.

THESE : para el plural de un objeto cercano.
THOSE : para el plural de objetos distantes.


This is my book // Este es mi libro.
That is your book over there on the desk // Aquel es tu libro, sobre la mesa.

PRONOMBRES RELATIVOS

Who (quien): para referirse a personas .// The man who telephoned was my brother.
Whom (a quien): The man whom you saw // El hombre a quien viste 
Whose(cuyo): the man whose sister 	you met yesterday . // El hombre cuya hermana conociste ayer.



Some (algunos): en oraciones positivas.

someone: alguien
somewhere: en alguna parte
something: 	algo.

Any ( ninguno ): en oraciones negativas.
anyone ( alguno ).
anything (cualquier cosa).
anywhere (en cualquier lugar).

He has some friends.
I didn't hear anyone . 


SAY vs TELL ( decir - comunicar algo  VS contar - contar/comunicar a alguien )


José me dijo la verdad - José told me the truth 
Pacho dijo algo - Pacho says something 



ALSO y TOO

ALSO ( olso )

Después del verbo to be : I'm also in class 
Antes del verbo común: They also want to dance  
Entre el auxiliar , modal y verbo : We could ALSO sing  ( entre el modal y el común )


TOO: se usa al final de la oración

I'm in class too.
They want to dance too.
We can sing too.





WHO: She is my doughter who is 4 years old

WHICH: ( el cual, cual )

My dog Spike, which is at the vet , jumps

WHOM (a quién, a quienes - jum ): They are our new friends, whom we met in Paris
- Our friends, whom we met in Paris, are in England.

WHOSE ( cuyo - posesivo - jus):

He is Michael, whose ( jus) son is John


THAT (que ): Luis is at the hotel, that is near his house.










